Barack Obama becomes the fourth US president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama arrives in Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to accept the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth US President in history.
In addition, he receives the diploma, the medal and a check for $1.4 million for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The head of the White House arrives tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the northern metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he pays a visit to the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The couple have scheduled a meeting with the Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its climax with the ceremony at which Obama takes over the prestige prize.
He is the fourth President of the United States, but only the third to receive the award directly in office.
The White House has already warned that Obama will talk about the Afghanistan war when he takes over the award.
The president does not want to dodge this issue because he knows that he is taking the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
He stepped up the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gold medal, diploma and cheque for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money to charity, but he has not yet decided on a specific charitable work.
The program of events will include a banquet with the President and his wife, at which, in addition to Norway’s King and Queen, the Prime Minister and another 250 invited guests will be present.
Obama has been very cautious about the price from the start.
He said, for example, that he felt that he did not quite deserve the prize.
He also repeated several times that the price is not just for him, but for all those who aspire to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that for him this is "invitation to action".
