USA: Repetition is Mother of Wisdom
It is almost comical with which student aspiration Barack Obama, the president with his call of the wisest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor in the Afghanistan question, which he himself considered to be the stupidest.
When he finally sweated out his much-anticipated Afghanistan doctrine, it turned out that he copied it from the copy paper from the Bush-Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he even used the name of the January 2007 Bush Declaration as the name of his own declaration: "New Forward" without hesitation.
Three years ago, he himself criticized the Bush idea of sending fresh contingents of troops to Iraq, which was plagued by the civil war, as an “irresponsible and, in its consequences, karastrophic decision.”
The following months showed, however, that the Bush strategy, which was based on recommendations from the military, was the only possible and very successful strategy in that it is no longer talked about in the news about Iraq at all.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, because objectively he left his successor with a much more grateful initial situation than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will repeat itself.
The military once again asked him to increase the troop contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghanistan operation General Stanley McCristal, who even despite the subordination habits harshly criticized the raging gunmen in the White House.
He called for 40,000 soldiers to be able to reverse the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but did not come up with a better idea, and so he cheated the general around 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe, he has pressed the commitment for another 5,000, even if he originally expected at least 10,000.
Most problematic of the entire Obama strategy is his plan to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months, and to complete this process within three years. The entire Obama Doctrine leaves more questions than answers.
Some doubt that the halved increase will have the same effect as the measure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal war of recent years, Iraq society is relatively well structured, its leaders honor the values.
The Afghan situation is marked by the contraindication - no one can be relied on and no agreements are kept.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, who are used to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if they were formally established correctly, remain only sham buildings, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to proliferate.
The balancing of interests between the different ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially because of the ambiguity of the circumstances, which complicate the Pakistan and Iran influences even further.
Also, the building of a "capable state of action", which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, is very unrealistic.
Time horizon of Obama strategy alienated by his voluntarism
Over the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and now it is on the verge of explosion.
Believing that the little soldiers who have broken out into the war cry about the "early homecoming" create a miracle here can only a truly romantic soul, which is not impressed by facts.
From a political point of view, the date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, because the Taliban will take this as the indirect confession of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in the fighting in Afghanistan is running low.
Europe’s politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the Hindu Kush foothills.
Another possible factor that can radically influence the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, a very serious question arises for the United States as to whether the problem cannot be solved with troops.
This question must be answered in the period when America is moving to the winner’s exit from Afghanistan after Obama.
Any solution, however, will also mean a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is the fact that there are still three years left until the presidential election, and thus there is still enough time for him to resort to a different strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
