The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from the VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the reproduction of the HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus proliferation in a different way than all drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new <0xCC><0x81>improved <0xCC><0x81> compounds, which have been prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two polyvalent cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Insidious and persistent virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus cleavage caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would be formed.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the proliferation of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work, published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further altered.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in test tubes, also against their resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of the metalocarboranes on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as in the clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants, against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical formation, make the metalocarborans interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective anti-HIV drugs, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Structural Biology Laboratory of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
