This new generation is trying to open the debate about how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen on the other in a modern secular society.
They don’t have all the arguments on their side.
The conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists Bowen interviewed are mostly at odds with their Salafi counterparts—supporters of purist Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia—who today show a small but influential presence among Europe’s Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires a give and take on both sides.
He questions the extent to which French political decision-makers (and the intellectual elite, who so passionately guard the separation of church and state) are truly committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may experience harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who, in turn, have had to make their historic compromise with secular republicanism.
He recognises a "tightening of the value screws" rather than a growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book, one is inclined to say "Yes, but not yet".
The most bleak view in the world
The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatically than any other environmental region on Earth.
The ice that marks them melts at an alarming rate, taking life with it that can’t survive anywhere else.
Oil, gas, shipping and fishing interests have moved into the recently open water, with diplomats, lawyers and now authors in their wake.
Richard Ellis, an author and illustrator, draws in "On Thin Ice" (original title: "On Thin Ice") a natural history of the icon of the North, the polar bear.
Involved in the complicated history and politics of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers who have proven themselves in the hunt for polar bears.
Admiral Nelson’s encounter with a polar bear as a brave 14-year-old ensign at sea who fought only with the butt of his musket is certainly a legend, but others are true.
Young bears caught swimming behind the bodies of their recently killed mothers were taken to zoos and circuses.
A circus performance at the beginning of the 20th century featured 75 polar bears at a performance.
Even today, zoos still typically have a millionth of the habitat of an old wild animal. The climate is rarely suitable: The polar bear in Singapore became completely green from the algae that grow in the hollow hairs of its fur.
Click here to learn more!
Ellis refers to the accounts of other authors and historians and often returns to the threat that hunters pose to the species’ survival.
Although banned in Norway, America and Russia, the killing continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and snowmobile-riding Inuit use powerful assault rifles to hunt down their prey.
Ironically, the ice will last the longest in the waters to the north of these two hunting nations.
In his new book, After the Ice, Alun Anderson, a former editor of the science magazine New Scientist, offers a clear and disturbing description of the science of the Arctic and a gripping insight into how the future might unfold.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of change.
However, this is not due to a lack of explanation.
The pioneering journeys of Fridtjof Nansen at the end of the 19th and beginning of the 20th century hinted for the first time at the turbulence of the pack ice.
In the Cold War, submarines measure the shifting ridges as they go under.
A useful addition are satellite surveys and the large-scale application of measuring probes on icebergs, but still much is achieved by intrepid people camping outside in the cold.
Anderson takes a look at the peculiar, tiny world of the inflow system within the Arctic ice, which is formed by saltwater mandrels compressed during freezing.
But, from the bear on the ice to the microscopic marvels in the ice, all are at risk once the summer ice passes, which is expected in the period between 2013 and 2050.
"In a few months... this could be us"
Marines were among the 6,000 who laid wreaths at Arlington.
De'Angello Robinson travelled by bus for seven hours to lay a single wreath on the grave of a soldier he had never met.
For him and the other Marines who made the journey from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina, to the National Cemetery in Arlington to decorate graves, the day was a tribute to the men and women in whose footsteps they have followed.
“In a few months, wherever we’re brought back from, that could be us,” Robinson said of the fallen soldiers.
If we were, I would wish someone would do the same for me, so I try to show my respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who had gathered on Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans in several sections of the Arlington Cemetery.
Morrill Worcester, owner of the Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, founded this tradition in 1992 when he and several others decided to decorate several hundred graves in the Arlington cemetery.
It is now an 18-year-old tradition and Morrill and his wife Karen, who take this trip every year, stop in different cities along the way to hold events dedicated to people in the military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcesters also founded a non-profit organization, Wreaths Across America, which expanded the event to other states.
This year, volunteers laid more than 16,000 wreaths on the graves at Arlington Cemetery, in areas at the Pentagon, at graves at Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, at Battery Park in New York, and at the memorial for United Airlines Flight 93 in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second time, the Walmart Foundation donated more than $150,000 to purchase and transport the wreaths.
Charleen Hunt, 70, from Westminster, said she made the trip to Arlington in memory of her husband, a deceased professional soldier.
Although her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said, this is her way of giving back to those who made sacrifices.
She said this is a small contribution to how we civilians can support our soldiers.
It’s like visiting a family cemetery.
Wrapped in layers of warm clothing, the volunteers wandered across the extensive lawns and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers targeted older graves from World War I and World War II and the Vietnam War, as these are not visited as often as the newer graves, according to the organizers.
The mood was cheerful, children were playing and couples were holding hands as they carried the fresh pine branches to the graying gravestones.
Each round wreath was dark green with a small red ribbon attached to the upper part.
Section 60, which is located nearby and where mainly veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried, remained almost calm.
The United Service Organizations donated 1,000 wreaths to adorn this section, but the gloomy mood of the current wars filled this area.
Individuals wept openly, others prayed, and families and friends held on to each other in the icy air.
Some read aloud the names carved in stone, while others leaned down to small black and white place cards that had been put in the damp mud for those whose tombstones had not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers who shed bitter tears in front of her son’s grave.
She traveled 8 hours from Zanesfield, Ohio, to visit the burial place of Marine Infranty Sergeant David Shane Spicer, who fell in combat in July.
No one should ever forget why we are free..., my son paid for it, she said.
“When I’m gone for a long time, I want someone to remember him.”
US government contractors arrested by Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has arrested a U.S. government contractor who sold mobile phones and notebook computers in the country, State Department officials said Saturday.
The contractor, who has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc., based in Bethesda.
The company works on projects for clients such as USAID, the US Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
Consular officials at the U.S. representation of interests in Havana are trying to gain access to the prisoner who was arrested on December 5.
The special charges have not yet been released, although under Cuban law, a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be arrested for almost anything, under the accusation of "threat."
All so-called counter-revolutionary activities, which include light protests and critical writings, pose a risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and statements are considered a serious crime.
Cuba has a growing blogging community led by popular reporter Yoani S<0xC3><0xA1>nchez, who often describes how she and her husband are being persecuted and attacked by government officials.
S<0xC3><0xA1>nchez has repeatedly asked for permission to leave the country to accept prices, but this has always been rejected.
The arrest of an American contractor is likely to heighten tensions between the Castro brother’s communist government in Cuba and the Obama administration, which had sought a “slow” rapprochement to improve relations with the island.
The news of the arrest was first reported Friday night by the New York Times.
The new U.S. policy emphasizes that the United States will pay in return if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as releasing political prisoners and creating more room for opposition.
Mobile phones and notebooks are legal in Cuba, although they are new and sought-after products in a country where the average earnings of a government employee is $15 per month.
The Cuban government has only allowed ordinary citizens to buy a mobile phone since this year, they are mainly used for sending text messages, since a 15-minute phone call would cost a day’s pay.
Internet use on the island is extremely limited.
It is accessible in expensive hotels and there for foreign visitors and at some government offices, such as universities.
Cubans who want to log in often have to report their names to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
In Cuba, the arrest of an American is rare.
Most of the few U.S. citizens who are in prison in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, the press secretary for the U.S. representation of interests in Havana.
Berbena said she could not provide any further information on the arrest.
The arrest and detention are clearly wrong.
An activity that would be legal in any other free society - the giving of free mobile phones - is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, head of the American section of the group "Human Rights Watch", which recently released a hard report on freedom in Cuba entitled "New Castro, same Cuba", a nod to the inauguration of Raul Castro as leader of the country, replacing the sick older brother Fidel.
Vivanco said the defendants were very often arrested, convicted and imprisoned within a day.
He said that probably any solution would be political and that the Cuban government often provokes a negative reaction in the United States, just at the time when both countries are moving toward more willingness to dialogue with each other.
Pakistani government officials reveal plan to send men to Afghanistan
Pakistani authorities discovered on Saturday a purportedly leading head of a conspiracy aimed at sending five men from northern Virginia to Afghanistan to kill U.S. soldiers, saying they hope this case could help uncover an extensive network of terrorist recruiters scouring the Internet for radicalized young men.
Investigators said they were looking for an opaque insurgent, known as Saifullah, who invited the men to Pakistan after he tracked them down because one of them made approving comments about terrorist attacks on the internet video site YouTube.
Saifullah became the leader of these men after their arrival in Pakistan, trying to help them reach the remote area in Pakistan’s tribal belt that is home to Al Qaeda and its terrorist training camps.
But a Pakistani intelligence official who was briefed on the matter said on Saturday Saifullah could not convince al-Qaeda leaders that the men were not part of a CIA plot to infiltrate the terrorist network.
As a result, they were held for days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far from the inhospitable mountains in the northwest that have become a terrorist refuge.
They were seen as part of a covert operation.
Therefore, they were rejected, said the government official, who wanted to remain anonymous due to the sensitivity of the matter.
The government official said the men were by no means discouraged and continued to try to get the right recommendations to gain access to the Al Qaeda camps when they were arrested by Pakistani correctional authorities.
The case of the five men - who remain in Pakistan and are being questioned by the FBI - underscores the crucial role of recruiters in identifying future terrorists and, perhaps more importantly, in deciding who is trustworthy.
Since the attacks of September 11, 2001, U.S. intelligence has made it a matter of the utmost urgency to house human assets within Al Qaeda.
The recruiters of the organization act as gatekeepers, not letting in those whose commitment to the Holy War is not serious enough and those who could be spies.
American would-be recruits are subjected to a special audit by A Qaeda, analysts said.
However, due to their potential access to U.S. goals and propaganda value, they are also considered tremendously attractive to the group.
Evan Kohlmann, senior analyst at the US-based NEFA Foundation, said terrorist groups have also become much more cautious in recent years about who they allow access to, as US intelligence agencies have become experts in their recruitment methods.
If you are trying to inject someone into these groups, what better way to go than to follow the recruitment model that so many have already followed?, Kohlmann said.
The model is now much more based on the Internet.
Tens of thousands of demonstrators in Copenhagen call for climate "action"
Tens of thousands of demonstrators marched through the streets here on Saturday, demanding that negotiators in the city’s Bella Congress Centre take bolder action on climate protection.
Protesters said 100,000 people had joined the event, while police estimates were more likely to be around 25,000.
The event was relatively peaceful, although a handful of masked activists detonated small explosive devices near some government buildings in the downtown area.
On a day when little happened in the UN-sponsored climate negotiations, thousands of activists marched through the city with banners that read “There is no Planet B” in English and one in Spanish that declared “The Earth says “enough.”
Some stars joined the protest, for example the Danish model, photographer Helena Christensen, who said the trips to Peru, her mother’s country of birth, made her aware of the heartbreaking problems the country is facing due to the already perceptible effects of climate change.
That’s part of the motivation for why I decided to take part in the big demonstration – to spread the word and appeal to world leaders to come up with a fair, ambitious and binding agreement, she said.
It is not an easy task, but it must be done now and there is no way around it.
Police stopped protesters from getting too close to Bella Center, saying they had arrested 19 people, mainly due to the fact that they were either masked or carrying pocket knives.
According to Danish law, these actions are prohibited during demonstrations.
According to a spectator who did not want to be named because he is involved in the climate negotiations, masked demonstrators in black clothing detonated several explosive devices near the Copenhagen main canal, near which there are several ministries.
They threw them near the buildings, he said, adding that they started as flares but were then followed by “a few big explosions.”
Inside the convention center, people gathered in front of television screens to watch the demonstration all afternoon.
But the protest has apparently not reached the consciousness of key officials, such as Su Wie, China’s chief climate negotiator.
When asked if he thought the demonstration would have a constructive effect on international considerations, he replied in English: “That’s something I wasn’t even aware of.”
He then continued in Mandarin, saying, “Because the venue is big, I can’t hear what’s happening outside.”
He noted that it depends on the perspective of the individual whether the demonstration would harm or help.
It shows the focus of the general public and different sectors on the issue of climate change, he said.
On the other hand, "you can also say that they disturb the negotiations or the freedom of other people".
Test data show persistent racial divide
The math performance testimonials were welcome good news for Washington D.C. public schools last week.
Although the Washington district is still far behind the country’s top-performing schools, the evidence shows that fourth- and eighth-graders have made faster progress over the past two years than cities that include Atlanta, Chicago, and New York.
But what is included in the latest figures from the National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) is the persistent achievement gap between African-American and white students, both at the local and national levels.
The average score of white fourth-graders from Washington D.C. rose from 262 to 270 (on a scale of 500) in the last two years, but that of their African-American peers only rose by three points from 209 to 212.
The performance gap actually increased from 53 to 58 points between 2007 and 2009.
The progress of the African-American eighth graders remained basically the same, dropping by a statistically negligible point from 245 to 244.
The average score of white students was not included in the test data as the sample size was not large enough.
The picture over a six-year period is also not more encouraging.
The gap that separated white and black fourth graders in 2003 when the first NAEP was recorded in that district was 60 scale points (262 to 202).
And although the score achieved by children of both groups has increased in this time span, the difference has hardly decreased by 58 points now.
Some education advocates of the district expressed concern last week that the results, celebrated by school chancellor Michelle A. Rhee and Democratic mayor Adrian M. Fenty, were largely driven by white students who are already high-performing children anyway.
This suggests that we have raised the overall rating by treating those at the top of the scale, which is problematic and difficult, said Jeff Smith, board member of D.C. Voice, a nonprofit group advocating for educational equality in Washington, D.C.
“I’m not jumping up and down for a span of two or three points,” said Democratic Washington City Councilman Kwame R. Brown, who has a daughter in the fourth grade of Eaton Elementary School.
Brown, a frequent critic of Rhee’s management style, said the message of exam scores is that the city’s middle schools need urgent attention.
Of course, you always want to see the positive signs, I respect that.
What scares me, however, is that we don’t spend nearly the time and energy we would have to devote to our middle school.
Rhee said the district must continue to find better ways to meet the needs of low-achieving students.
This fall, for example, some teachers are being trained to use a new reading curriculum, the Wilson Reading System, which targets students in the upper grades of elementary and middle school who have not mastered basic reading skills at the beginning of their school career and who are significantly behind their peers.
Everyday mathematics, a curriculum that focuses from kindergarten to sixth grade games and lifelike experiences, was brought to Washington under former Principal School Inspector Clifford Janey, and this curriculum is credited with some of the NAEP advances reported last week.
I think we need to keep working to ensure that the best measures benefit students who are below grade level, Rhee said.
Others say the NAEP results highlight the question of whether Rhee can continue to improve the overall performance of the system while continuing to provide the additional money and resources to the low-performing schools that are needed to reduce the gap.
This is a serious dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, a professor of education at the University of California at Berkeley who studies urban exam results.
The conventional remedy is to direct its resources and management reforms to the schools located in the poorest areas of Washington, D.C.
The objective could produce political repercussions that work against this important item on the agenda.
The weak point, of course, as with other city school inspectors, is that they are trying to keep the white and black middle class.
Our focus is to make sure we build a system of great schools.
We need to strengthen our schools in the neighborhoods so that all families, regardless of where they live, can be sure that their children can receive excellent public education.
Janey, who is now a school inspector in Newark, said in an interview this week that one of the most significant elements in closing the achievement gap is extending the traditional public school year, which is currently 180 days in Washington, to compete with charter schools.
One has to increase the school year to approximately 200 days in order to have the strength to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with his teachers’ union last year for 185 days a year, which he sees as “a milestone” on the way to a greater increase in the next contract.
Higher education for more people as a future prospect
The coach reaches Gettysburg College with a loud whistle.
Graciela Rodriguez, 12, steps out and blinks for a moment at the sight of the white columns, the brick facades and the emerald green lawn.
Graciela’s parents barely graduated from high school in El Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela, who was recovered in Silver Spring and now lives in Riverdale, had never set foot on a college campus.
Their attitude, and that of the group’s other eighth-graders exploring Gettysburg, where tuition costs $38,690 a year, was that of an awe-inspiring visitor rather than that of an enthusiastic future student.
"Yes, I'll be here soon!" cried Graciela, who would like to study medicine, when the Fuehrer announced that they had now entered the Natural Sciences building.
"Wow, really?" she said thoughtfully when she was told the low professor-to-student ratio of the school.
College in Pennsylvania was the 7th the children visited on their three-day tour and now they have fully embraced the intended message: the question is not whether to go to college.
The question is where.
On the one hand, there is growing concern about the large number of Hispanic immigrant children born in the U.S. who do not finish high school or become pregnant as a teenager, but on the other hand, there are hundreds of thousands who receive the college education needed to advance to the middle class.
In fact, one in five of these “second generation” Hispanics graduate from college — which is a remarkable achievement as many of their immigrant parents, mostly from Mexico or Central America, came to the U.S. without graduating high school.
Their success stories are important, researchers say, because they show the way forward for a generation that will play a huge role in the country’s workforce.
Those who study high-performing children say they often have a natural affinity for school and an inherent drive for success.
Many of them also have parents who set high goals for their children and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
But counseling programs also play a big role in helping Graciela and millions of children like her get into college, especially if those efforts persist over a longer period of time.
If you look at low-income children whose parents don’t have the experience and skills to help them navigate the system, then a single measure at some point won’t solve the problem either, said Patricia G<0xC3><0xA1>ndara, a researcher at the University of California at Davis who studied Hispanic American students.
We need to think about providing a supportive network for these children from preschool through high school.
The federal program that funded Graciela’s college tour is a useful example.
It’s known as GEAR UP—turning up a gear—and provides more than $300 million a year for local school systems to launch college preparatory programs that start when low-income students are in middle school and continue to run until they graduate from high school.
According to the U.S. Department of Education, the program has helped more than 10 million students since 1999, more than 60% of whom have gone to college.
Iraqi oil ministry signs contracts with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite concerns about violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has been able to get major oil companies to rebuild its damaged infrastructure at two auctions closed on Saturday.
The 10 contracts signed with foreign oil companies by the Iraqi Oil Ministry suggest that China, Russia and European oil companies are ready to play an important role in renovating Iraq’s oil industry, which has been paralyzed by war and economic sanctions for decades.
American companies were only able to book shares in two of the 10 auctioned fields for themselves.
Seven American companies had paid to participate in the second auction, which began on Friday.
The only company that has made a bid has pulled the short end of the stick.
Two American companies were able to conclude contracts for fields auctioned in June.
The thinly-seeded representatives of American oil multinationals at the opening of the Iraqi oil industry surprised the analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors after 6 years of war and instead of U.S. companies Asian and European are leading the way, said Ruba Husari, the editor of Iraq Oil Forum, an online news service.
There will be no more offers in Iraq for a long time.
Security concerns highlighted by massive coordinated bombings on Tuesday and the political instability caused by the withdrawal of the U.S. military have likely deterred U.S. oil companies, analysts said, from getting more involved in Iraq, which holds the world’s third-largest proven crude reserves.
