U.N. High Representative in Kabul to Resign
The UN’s leading envoy to Afghanistan, Kai Eide, said on Friday that he would step down from his post in March, ending a stormy term clouded by allegations of widespread corruption in the UN-backed Afghan presidential election.
The Obama administration decided to send another 30,000 U.S. troops to Afghanistan.
The U.N. envoy said he supports the troop increase, but he also expressed his concerns that the U.S. military withdrawal schedule, scheduled to begin in 18 months, could prompt other NATO governments to withdraw their forces.
We need to speed up the build-up of Afghan security forces and thereby send the right signal to Afghans that they can trust the international community, Eide said in a telephone interview from Kabul.
The commitment must be long-term.
The Norwegian diplomat also urged the United States and other military powers to increase the number of international civilian aides to help in Afghanistan’s political transition.
The increase in troops on the military side must correspond to an increase on the civilian side, he said.
Eide said that he was not resigning, but only fulfilling an agreement made in March 2008 to his family to stay in Kabul for only two years.
He said he wanted to send a message to the UN.
Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon is now passing on so that he has time to provide for a replacement.
What I said is that he better start looking for a successor, Eide said.
When I came here, there was a two-month vacuum between my predecessor’s departure and my arrival.
