A change of course in aging China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters giving them lectures that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain more children" and "One more baby means one more grave".
These lessons they learned so well that when government officials in Shanghai, who suddenly began to change course this summer due to the low birth rate and aging population, and encouraged young couples to have more than one child, their answer was immediate and definitive: “No way.”
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
There is nothing left for a second child, said Wang, 31, a human resources manager with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which has spawned two generations of notoriously thick, warped single children affectionately called “little emperors,” a population crisis is looming in the country.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time this policy came into force, the UN
According to the Department of Population Affairs, the number of people aged 60 and over is expected to increase from 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent by 2050, well above the global average of around 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and older people accounted for nearly 22 percent of Shanghai’s reported residents, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City Population and Family Planning Commission, has said that couples of childbearing age must have babies to “help reduce the ratio of aging populations and alleviate the labor shortage of the future.”
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as developed countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
Enshrined in the country’s 1978 constitution, China’s one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial decree introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Couples who violate this policy face huge fines -- up to their triple annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplace.
Chinese state officials have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of the country’s natural resources could be avoided, while human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who already had a child to abort.
Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions, creating an unnaturally high male-to-female ratio.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their stance on one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007, the tone of many hard slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Beijing University’s Institute of Population Research, said government officials have recently even discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children where a partner is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines detailing who qualifies for a second child and how to apply for approval.
The city government has sent city employees and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and push through information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The response was not exactly encouraging, family planning representatives said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outskirts of Shanghai said that an upturn in the applications of couples who want a second child after the start of the campaign can be seen, the urban districts, on the other hand, report no change.
For the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, as an example, only four to five applications are still received per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births expected in the city in 2010 will still be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Caolu Family Planning Committee in Shanghai Municipality, said that financial considerations were probably the main reason why many people don’t want to have more children.
They want to give their first best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that this is also legally permissible.
But they, like many Chinese, have only a small amount of health and life insurance from the government.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West mistakenly rate the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yes, we are robbed of the opportunity to have more than one child.
The problem is not just in politics.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the head of human resources, said she only wants a child because she was also an only child. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We’re not used to taking care of others and we don’t really want to.”
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it more bluntly.
For middle-class parents with dual careers, through which the birth rate drops, he said, it’s all about being successful and for that you have to be selfish.
The 20- to 39-year-olds grew up watching their parents struggle during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment, and they don’t want such a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, places huge demands on the time of parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the spatial question -- "You have to rebuild your apartment" -- and the life planning -- "When the child is 9 months old, you already have a resume for the best preschools ready."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to reach a higher standard of living, he said.
We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group Drafts Plan to Reduce Emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterized by wild poses and mutual accusations -- has again put a spotlight on Friday with the publication of a document that will record an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with industrialized nations shouldering the biggest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, showed both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it has been seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that will run out of time as more than 100 top politicians from around the world arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, which was drafted by a specially created UN working group, remains silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can master global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for the key issues, including how developed and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and how high should be the upper limit of global temperature rise that policy makers would support.
The process is given great flexibility, according to John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN’s leading climate protection official, Yvo de Boer, has called “the big picture.”
It shows the floor plan of a possible agreement in which industrialized nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also boosted the talks on Friday by committing to providing $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impacts of climate change, from mastering floods and droughts to avoiding deforestation.
Friday nevertheless brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the talks last week.
U.S. Special Envoy for Climate Change Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for binding greenhouse gas emissions reductions for developed countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if not funded by industrialized nations.
This move announced that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China than representatives of the Bush administration did less than two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging economies standing up and taking action, said Stern, who also complained that the text does not go far enough to ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern issued his statement an hour after China’s Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said the leading American climate negotiator was either lacking in “reason” or it was “highly irresponsible” of him to say earlier this week that the United States would not help China financially master global warming.
Because the future economic march of the great world powers is at stake, fault lines have opened up both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle is equally concerned with saving individual economies, as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States contending for their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the big powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to be more aggressive in holding the very high greenhouse gas tax countries accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic hegemony will develop, according to Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although leading participants say the talks will lead to a political agreement at best.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States presented a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the small island nation’s offensive “exercises political pressure on the entire political process,” partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most open questions need to be resolved before the government leaders arrive to reach an agreement.
High-ranking officials, such as India’s Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China’s Vice Minister, stepped out of their planes and raced through the corridors of the Bella Center to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to stake out claims that will be negotiated during the next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people go in and out of the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists put on nightly shows making fun of the countries they believe are betraying and selling themselves, and draft contracts are handed out hand-to-hand rather than via email -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just beginning to build: almost all the important ministers are here now and from Wednesday, 60 government leaders will be in Copenhagen.
“We are coming to the Oberliga,” said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president of global politics at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
