The illusions are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, those affected can usually no longer distinguish between the inner and outer world, they get into an overexcited state, which can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship or persecution.
Voice-hearing is especially common - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not rare.
The affected person is no longer able to separate important from unimportant things, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis also opens the floodgates to a flood of ideas and fantasies emanating from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the event, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time he falls into a passive role, he is, like in a dream, overwhelmed by the events and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A reality comparison is usually not possible for them, the illusions are cruel reality, waking up excluded.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
In contrast to the dream, says Fuchs, “the sensuous and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, remains basically preserved.”
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real framework.
Why exactly our brain beats caprioles, researchers still pose puzzles.
Exceptional circumstances can cause every person to lose touch with reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that the genes are not the sole determining factors.
Researchers assume that there is minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that the neural maturation of the brain at an early stage of development is disrupted by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, for example, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery how the disruption of the neural system comes about, which also initially does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for a psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brain is hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get some, says the Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether illusions are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a question of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and cheats for ten years, last year he evaluated his results in the book "The unreal world in our head".
Hallucinations are among the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s and skull brain trauma.
Surprisingly, even the brains of healthy people hallucinate under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memory contents that are usually held back.
They occur when areas of the brain where sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or under-inhibited; when our brain is running hot or even when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also irritation, stress, heartache or other mental states of exception.
In more recent studies, up to a third of respondents reported having experienced hallucination at least once in their lifetime.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and attends the high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it weren't for the pictures and the voices.
During the break, it can happen that a lanky boy with long, dark hair addresses it.
If it answers him, the classmates look at it in surprise - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spunky daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bench next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she asks herself sometimes.
But she knows that this boy and the other illusions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening
Often the illusions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the teaching material, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is introducing a new classmate, while he explains mathematical equations for all the others on the board, both audible and visible.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which is far too rare and far too late, she often cannot distinguish whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees, the grimaces or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, arise in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Parents and friends don’t tell her about it, they would think she’s crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed her high school graduation last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she contacted the psychologist box on the internet, she knows she’s not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffering from irritable withdrawal, they are likely to have hallucinations after a while, Kasten says.
I suspect that the brain is then underemployed and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she calls dad since she can think is not her biological father.
Since the same areas of the brain are active in visual and acoustic hallucinations, which also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult to distinguish between illusions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is reflected there.
Hallucinations are also images that create the brain, which is why they seem so real."
Also, nocturnal dream pictures value box as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their delusions as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to also value the hallucinations as a special ability.
Boundary state between dream and hallucination
In our too mind-centered world, imaginary experience is unfortunately mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Clinic for Psychiatry and Psychotherapy of the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also contains positive, creative - delusion is also a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of the traumatically altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroides are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer considers to be real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state even in retrospect.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma- or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with loss of self and world, for example by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own, imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of boundary state between dream and hallucination.
Since coping with a situation in reality is not possible, a world change takes place, but the real situation is made present in the imagination.
An intensive form of meaning creation and giving meaning in an inherently intolerable situation, which allows us humans own creative ability, not to sink into a nothing of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in the memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his Oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" as a rescue of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve operation followed by a heart transplant, while his body is condemned to immobility in the intensive care unit.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, on board a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who make intoxicants from blood.
Being kidnapped by a Greek on a motorcycle in his home country, surfs with his hospital bed in the firn snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
He is completely absorbed in the imagined events, everything is real, even later in the memory.
These inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream for Claussen.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental journeys are still clear to me after years and in minor details.
More intense and even more intense than the real thing.
The intensity of this experience is beyond the horizon of our other life-worldly experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, oneiroids, psychosis, hallucinations and drug intoxication show how fragile our inner images of external reality are even in waking.
Any change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist Kasten concludes, “can lead to a deformation of what we call reality.”
An experience that can also be enriching.
