Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study "Fertility and Career of Women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged between 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market restricted due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are large differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and if so, what kind of profession they pursue.
Those of them who do not perform any other activity outside the home, work only half-days or do not have a fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a permanent job, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore also have fewer children.
"The women in the age group between 35 and 49 years of age with a permanent employment get their first child on average only 3.7 years after the contraction, a number that increases to 4.1 years for women with permanent employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have realized their contraction and the first child much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a great influence on motherhood, although less than the calendar in terms of willingness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women at marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference could also be observed in women of the same age.
For example, the women in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, depending on whether they only have a high school diploma or a higher education, became mothers for the first time, on average, at 25.1 or 32.1 each.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with a high school diploma get married before their first permanent job and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school diploma do it the other way around and first look for a permanent job and then marry and then have their first child, Delgado notes.
