The sale of small trucks is increasing somewhat again
After almost two years, the car market for vans is finally starting to see some light at the end of the dark tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in Spain in November represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, the first increase ever after 22 consecutive months of steady decline, according to the figures presented by the Anfac Association and the Ganvam Association of Car Dealers.
However, these good figures are currently to be enjoyed with great caution, as the reference data used for comparison are from November 2008, which was a particularly bad sales year with a 60 % decrease compared to the previous year.
However, it should be borne in mind that, apart from the increase in the last month, the total approvals of these 11 months are still 40% below the sales figures of the previous fiscal year.
Since January, a total of 95,853 vehicles have been sold, but this figure includes all vehicles that make up the van market: descendants of passenger cars, pick-ups, vans, small vans and lighter light trucks/carriages.
Furthermore, the same storm clouds are still in the sky, which affect demand the most, because even if some of the vehicles are bought by private individuals, the majority of sales go to small and medium-sized enterprises, which in almost 100% of all cases make the purchase with a third-party financing.
Thus, these restrictions, which are the result of the shut-down of the financial institutions, must include other factors, such as the increase in the unemployment rate or the continuation of the bad economic situation.
With this panorama and unlike the passenger cars, the financial support provided for the purchase of a vehicle of the Plan 2000E has been of little help.
