Just yesterday Ganvam reminded that it is absolutely necessary on the part of the state to pay special attention to these small trucks as well as, of course, to industrial vehicles (trucks and buses).
The Car Dealers Association predicts a similar year for 2010 as the just past, for which it expects a sales loss (for passenger cars and off-road vehicles) of 19%.
Support in braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system back then and as is currently the case with stability control ESP, the emergency braking assistance systems must become mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, for the remaining vehicles a grace period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The action decided by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but because of their working methods, these braking systems can also help to prevent many rear-end collisions.
The task of the emergency braking assistant is to apply more pressure to the brakes in the event of a critical braking maneuver, which the system recognizes on the brake pedal on the basis of the braking force carried out by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even get on the brake pedal before the collision, and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, engages with maximum force in the brake system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance covered by a car during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents – one in four accidents with personal injury is expected to be prevented – as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system helps to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if it becomes necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already unavoidable, the Brake Assist exerts maximum pressure on the brakes to keep the damage as low as possible.
