The French company Bouygues and the German Hochtief are its competitors.
A 5-kilometer tunnel in the Australian city of Brisbane, on the east coast, has become the best opportunity for Acciona to establish itself in the country as a construction company and motorway operator.
The City Council expects the construction to be completed by the end of 2014.
After the Public-Private Cooperation Administration (PPP) decided to move the project forward according to a business plan drawn up by Ernst & Young, the Administration already has a definitive list of candidates for construction and toll booth management.
In anticipation of the offers presented in May, the estimated investment amounts to 1.7 billion Australian dollars (1,047 billion euros), with three consortia, mainly consisting of European construction companies, competing in the final phase.
The Transcity group is led by Acciona, the only Spanish company, and its partners are BMD and Ghella.
The first company is one of the largest construction companies in Australia, while the second, based in Italy, is one of the best specialists in civil engineering.
The Northern Direct consortium will compete against the Acciona team, consisting of the British company Laing O'Rourke, the Australian Transfield, which is responsible for the infrastructure, and the French Bouygues sub-assembly.
The third and final shortlisted consortium is LBRJV, made up of the capital of the Australian Leighton (subsidiary of the German construction company Hochtief, which in turn belongs to ACS), the also native Baulderstone (owned by the German group Bilfinger Berger) and the French company Razel, which specializes in public construction.
The Australian infrastructure market promises huge construction and privatisations, but has a hurdle to overcome, as you can only access it by buying a local construction company.
A strategy followed by the mentioned companies Hochtief or Bilfinger, in addition to Asian references, and which has yet to be pursued by the Spanish construction giants.
Even ACS has only gained access to this market through its 30% stake in Hochtief, owner of Leighton.
